"Written evidence submitted by the General Council of the Bar of England and Wales (LAI 0040) &#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nOverview&#xa0;\na)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe proposed introduction of a residence test for civil legal aid claimants, so as to limit legal aid to those with a “strong connection” with the UK – ‘the \nresidence test\n’\nb)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe proposed \nrestriction on the scope of legal aid available to prisoners – ‘prison law’\nc)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe proposal that providers of legal services in applications for judicial review against public bodies should only be paid for work done on the case if the Court grants permission\n for the application to proceed – ‘judicial review’\n,\n and\nd)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe proposal that legal aid should be removed fo\nr all cases assessed as having \n“\nborderline\n”\n prospects of success – ‘borderline cases’\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nResidence testOverview \n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\na)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \n‘Lawful’\n – determining\n whether\n a person is lawfully resident \nmay \nin itself \nrequire access to the courts. Legal aid, however, would not be available to \nre\nsolve a dispute as to the lawfulness of residence.\nb)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \n‘Residence’\n – \nBritish children resident abroad\n could be precluded\n from obtaining legal aid to bring a claim in th\ne Family Court that they should be returned to the UK. It would also preclude persons wrongly removed from the UK\n \nfrom being eligible for legal aid to pursue their claim\n for damages and/or lawful return\n.\nc)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \n‘Continuously’\n – \na person who r\nesided in the UK for \nsix months and then\n left the UK for periods amounting to more than 30 days could not rely on the previous period of six months to accumulate the qualifying 12 month period\n. \nd)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \n‘12 month period’\n – \na British citizen \nor E\nuropean \nE\nconomic \nA\nrea (EEA)\n national \nwho\n has lived abroad for a substantial period may \nbe unable to\n establish 12\n&#xa0;\nmonths residence in the UK as holders of British \nand EEA \npassports \ndo\n not have their passports stamped on entry to the UK\n \n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nImplications for h\numan \nr\nights\n \n&#xa0;\n“Habeas corpus protection is often expressed as limited to British subjects. Is it really limited to British nationals? Suffice \nit to say that the case law has given an emphatic ‘no’ to the question. Every person within the jurisdiction enjoys the equal protection of our la\nw\ns.\n.\n.He who is subject to English law is entitled to its protection.” \n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nDisproportionate \ni\nmpact \n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\na)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nRespondents in 1980 Hague Convention cases who have ‘fled’ to this jurisdiction or moved here with no sufficient connection to the UK\nb)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nApplicants in stat\nes not signatory to the 1980 Hague Convention seeking a return of children th\nere in wardship proceedings\nc)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nStranded spouses who have be\nen here for less than 12 months\nd)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nApplicants for contact on an application made pursuant to Article 12 of the \n1980 Hague Conv\nention\ne)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nApplicants for recognition made pursuant to the provisions of Brussels \nII\n \n(\nrevis\ned\n)\n,\n and\nf)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nApplicants for recognition and enforcement of a foreign order under the 1980 Hague Convention. \n&#xa0;\nUnintended consequences\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n              \nConclusion\n&#xa0;\nPrison lawOverview \n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nImplicat\nions for \nh\numan \nr\nights\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nUnintended c\nonsequences\n&#xa0;Judicial reviewOverview \n&#xa0;\nImplications for human r\nights\n&#xa0;\n“Where an infringement of an \nindividual's human rights has occurred, the concern will usually be to bring the infringement to an end and any question of compensation will be of secondary, if any, importance. This is reflected in the fact that, when it is necessary to resort to the cou\nrts to uphold and protect human rights\n, the remedies that are most frequently sought are the orders which are the descendants of the historic prerogative orders or declaratory judgments. The orders enable the court to order a public body to refrain from or\n to take action, or to quash an offending administrative decision of a public body.”\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nDisproportionate i\nmpact\n&#xa0;\na)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nAn application for permission carries a relatively high risk of initial failure. Even where a claim is meritorious it is often necessary to persist to an oral hearing or further to obtain permission. \nFor example, while \nWood v Commissioner of Police\n is now\n a leading case on privacy and police records, p\nermission\n for judicial review\n was only granted on appeal. \n \nb)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nJudicial review claims are “front loaded” in \nthat most of the work from the c\nlaimant’s perspective must be done at the stage of brin\ng\ning the claim. Practitioners therefore have to invest a large amount of time, cost and effort for which they may not get paid. This is increased still further if they have to proceed to an oral hearing or appeal. \nc)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nApplications for permission are difficult \nto predict and there is much variability among judges\n, and\nd)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nMany cases settle on beneficial terms after issue but before permission. It is not possible to tell how these are reflected in the statistics. Under the proposals these cases would not be paid for \nexcept on a discretionary basis.\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nUnintended c\nonsequences\n&#xa0;\nConclusion\n&#xa0;\nBorderline cases Overview \n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\na)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nC\nases which involve the prospect of a loss of a person’s home \n–\n engaging the human right to respect for the home (‘\nh\nousing’ cases)\n,\n  and \n \nb)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nC\nases which involve the prospect of the loss of a person’s children into the care system \n–\n engaging the right to respect for family lif\ne (‘\np\nublic law children’ cases)\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nImplicat\nions for human rights \n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nDisproportionate i\nmpact \n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nUnintended\n consequences\n&#xa0;\na)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nHow many cases were assessed as borderline but nevertheless received legal aid funding?\nb)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nIn what classes of case did this occur?\nc)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nHow many of those cases produced a benefit for the client (and cos\nts recovery)?\nd)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nHow many were actually lost and what did they cost?\n And,\ne)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nWhat, if any, are the common features of those that won/lost?\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;Table 1: Distribution of case types for cases for borderline cases in 2011/12 Case TypeCase typeProportion (%) Domestic Violence \n8\nHousing \n41\nImmigration and Asylum \n2\nPrivate Law Children Act \n3\nOther Public Law \n8\nOther Public Law Children\n \n38\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\na)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nInstead of making sensible and reasoned assessments (i.e. that the prospects cannot be precisely measured) where the pr\nospects are genuinely unclear, it will be necessary to err on the side of caution and assess at 51% where (as in all such cases presently falling into the scheme) something really important is at stake\nb)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nDecisions by the Director of Legal Aid which put the p\nrospects of success to be just less than 50% will lead to more appeals to Adjudicators\n,\n therefore tying up additional resources, and\nc)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nMore applications will be made for legal aid at the investigatory level to enable a more precise assessment of prospects \nof\n success, \nbuilding in additional cost and, often more importantly, delay.\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nSeptember\n 2013\n13\n&#xa0;\n £1 million from no longer funding borderline cases, £4\n&#xa0;\nm\nillion\n from changes to criminal legal aid for prison law and £1-3\n&#xa0;\nm\nillion\n for placing judicial review work at risk. The Government has not calculated projected savings for introducing a residence test due to lack of data. \n \nTransforming legal aid: next steps \n(2013), Ministry of Justice, Annex B: Response to consultation\n \nTran\nsforming legal aid: scope, eligibility and merits (civil legal aid): Impact assessment\n, \nIA No: MoJ194\n (2013), page 6\n \nex parte Khawaja\n [1984] AC 74 at 111G-112A\n \nR (Medical Justice) v Secretary of State for the Home Department\n [2011] EWCA Civ 1710 quashe\nd immigration removal policy as “unlawful because it abrogated the constitutional right of access to justice” and found that “in order to have effective access to the courts, the person served with removal direction…needs to have a reasonable opportunity t\no obtain legal advice and assistance”. See also \nR (Evans) v Lord Chancellor\n [2012] 1 WLR 838, paragraph 25 (Laws LJ): “For the state to inhibit litigation by the denial of legal aid because the court’s judgement might be unwelcome or apparently damaging wo\nuld constitute an attempt to influence the incidence of judicial decisions in the interests of government. It would therefore be highly inimical to the rule of law.”\n \nD\n&#xa0;\nv\n&#xa0;\nNational Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Children\n [1978] AC 171, 239G: \n“And\n if it comes to the forensic crunch...it must be law, not di\nscretion, which is in command”\n \nScott v Scott\n [1913] AC 417, 477\n \nTransforming Legal Aid: delivering a more credible and efficient system \n(2013), Ministry of Justice, paragraph 3.56\n \nTransformi\nng legal aid: next steps \n(2013), Ministry of Justice, Annex B: Response to consultation, paragraphs 125-126\n [2010] EWCA Civ 460\n Section 22(3)\n Section 55\n \nWright v Michael Wright Supplies and Anor\n [2013] EWCA Civ 234, (Ward LJ): “[S]aving expenditure\n in one public department in this instance simply increases it in the courts. The expense of three judges of the Court of Appeal dealing with this kind of appeal is enormous…With more and more self-represented litigants, this problem is not going to go awa\ny…[J]ustice will be ill served indeed by this emasculation of legal aid.”\n \nTransforming legal aid: next steps \n(2013), Ministry of Justice, Annex 